text_widget.alt_text: During the next season, Carlisle Institute, a small and unknown school, began defeating the great football powers of the day, Pennsylvania, Harvard, Yale, Pittsburgh, Chicago, West Point. At the time, Dwight Eisenhower was a cadet playing for the West Point team. Ordered by his coach to stop Thorpe, Eisenhower had the startling experience of seeing the great player thunder toward him, over him, and past him down the field for a long gain. Another football player during the period said that being in a game with Thorpe was less a matter of playing football than of staying out of his way.

text_widget.alt_text: Jim Thorpe was most celebrated for his stunning performance at the 1912 Olympics in Sweden. He received gold medals for the two most grueling competitions, the pentathlon, consisting of five separate events, and the decathlon, consisting of ten. His skill in swimming, running, throwing the javelin and the discus, and participating in other sports won high praise from King Gustav of Sweden, who called Thorpe the greatest athlete in the world.
